pybind11 tracks bound objects and reuses them if the type and C++ address match. That&#39;s why the second case works. I do not know the exact use case that you are describing, but if the attribute is always added in a function, then you can make sure the reference stays alive by tying it to the lifetime of the &#39;b&#39; object. Example:

    def func(b):
        b._sa = b.sa
        b.sa.pa = &#39;hello&#39;

or:

    def func(b):
        sa = b.sa
        b.__dict__[&#39;sa&#39;] = sa
        sa.pa = &#39;hello&#39;

If you have many objects of type &#39;A&#39;, the second approach will be more efficient.

